{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"doc_id": "86a1279b-cb08-49cb-90dc-50e2fa4b7caa", "source": "NexaCorp Policy Handbook v5.2", "part": "3. Human Resources Policies", "section": "3.2 Employment Classifications", "subsection": "3.2.2 Contractor Classification Test", "raw_content": "Before engaging any individual as an independent contractor rather than as an employee, the hiring department must complete a Worker Classification Assessment (WCA) through the Legal department. The following factors are evaluated as part of the test, broadly aligned with IRS Common Law Rules and applicable state tests (including California AB5 where applicable): Behavioural Control: Does the company control how the worker performs tasks, or only the result? Financial Control: Does the worker have significant investment in tools, work for multiple clients, and bear the risk of profit/loss? Type of Relationship: Is there a written contract, provision of employee-type benefits, and is the relationship indefinite or project-specific? IMPORTANT: In California, the ABC test under AB5 applies to most occupational classifications and creates a strong presumption of employee status. All California contractor engagements require mandatory pre-approval by the CLO's office.", "type": "text", "text": "Part: 3. Human Resources Policies\n            Section: 3.2 Employment Classifications\n            Subsection: 3.2.2 Contractor Classification Test\n            Before engaging any individual as an independent contractor rather than as an employee, the hiring department must complete a Worker Classification Assessment (WCA) through the Legal department. The following factors are evaluated as part of the test, broadly aligned with IRS Common Law Rules and applicable state tests (including California AB5 where applicable): Behavioural Control: Does the company control how the worker performs tasks, or only the result? Financial Control: Does the worker have significant investment in tools, work for multiple clients, and bear the risk of profit/loss? Type of Relationship: Is there a written contract, provision of employee-type benefits, and is the relationship indefinite or project-specific? IMPORTANT: In California, the ABC test under AB5 applies to most occupational classifications and creates a strong presumption of employee status. All California contractor engagements require mandatory pre-approval by the CLO's office."}, "page_content": "Part: 3. Human Resources Policies\n            Section: 3.2 Employment Classifications\n            Subsection: 3.2.2 Contractor Classification Test\n            Before engaging any individual as an independent contractor rather than as an employee, the hiring department must complete a Worker Classification Assessment (WCA) through the Legal department. The following factors are evaluated as part of the test, broadly aligned with IRS Common Law Rules and applicable state tests (including California AB5 where applicable): Behavioural Control: Does the company control how the worker performs tasks, or only the result? Financial Control: Does the worker have significant investment in tools, work for multiple clients, and bear the risk of profit/loss? Type of Relationship: Is there a written contract, provision of employee-type benefits, and is the relationship indefinite or project-specific? IMPORTANT: In California, the ABC test under AB5 applies to most occupational classifications and creates a strong presumption of employee status. All California contractor engagements require mandatory pre-approval by the CLO's office.", "type": "Document"}}